body:
This seems like a verilator lint bug, but I wouldn't be surprised if undefined by spec. Happy to convert to a test_regress if this is an actual bug

testcase.sv:
```
module testcase;

    typedef enum logic [1:0] { e_0, e_1, e_2, e_3 } enum_e;

    typedef struct packed {
        integer unsigned x;
        integer unsigned y;
    } foo_s;

    typedef struct packed {
        integer unsigned y;
    } bar_s;

    // Warning due to concatenation, but this is actually a member assignment
    localparam foo_s foo = '{
        y: (1 << e_0) | (1 << e_3)
        ,default: '0
    };

    // No warning
    localparam bar_s bar = '{
        y: (1 << e_0) | (1 << e_3)
    };

endmodule
```

> What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

```
verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-UNUSEDPARAM testcase.sv
...
%Warning-WIDTHCONCAT: testcase.sv:12:23: Unsized numbers/parameters not allowed in concatenations.
                                       : ... note: In instance 'testcase'
   12 |         y: (1 << e_0) | (1 << e_3)
      |                       ^
                      ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/WIDTHCONCAT?v=5.036
                      ... Use "/* verilator lint_off WIDTHCONCAT */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
```

> What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?

Verilator 5.037 devel rev v5.036-110-g5fcd0e52e (current master)

> What OS and distribution are you using?

Centos7

> May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

If trivial, sure! If non-trivial it will be low priority since it's just a warning.

